09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.01012d73-c59a-43dc-8894-f3926953cfd2.prompt=Password\: 09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.17bf50f3-43f3-4a83-8de5-28b1321776d0.description=Sorts a list. If this list is all numerical, it is sorted in numerical order, other wise it is sorted in alphabetical order. 
Inputs\:

09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.1d23cfa5-d7de-4679-870b-a6a28f5952cd.prompt=host\: 09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.23646e8c-a055-4d2e-b086-33e3c4ac799e.prompt=password\: 09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.23b25091-10ce-418c-84e3-6ae5b15b4f1b.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.
09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.418e1099-27e7-46cd-81ca-fd6a8d218105.description=
Returns details about how a datastore is mounted against all hosts.

Inputs\: 
    host - VMware vCenter, ESX or ESXi host hostname or IP.
    user - The VMware username.
    password - The VMware user's password. 
    port - The Port to connect to the VMware server.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - The connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Specifies whether to close the internally kept VMware Infrastructure API session when the operation completes. 
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    datacenter - The datacenter of the datastore.
    dataStore - The name of the datastore to get mount details about.

Responses\: 
    success - Datastore mount details were successfully retrieved.
    failure - Something went wrong.  See returnResult for details.

Results\:
    returnResult - A JSON array of objects describing how the datastore is mounted on each host.  Reason for error on failure.
09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.5536132e-e87c-4d64-ba38-9f992c3295fd.description=Search for VMWare objects and their properties from a root object (if any). Retrieve each object's properties one at a time from an initial search query as the one used for the SQL Query operation. Inputs\: host - VMWare host hostname or IP user - VMWare username password - VMWare user's password port - Port to connect on protocol - Connection protocol (http or https) closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation? propsType - VMWare properties type (Task, Datacenter, VirtualMachine, etc.) to filter on propsPathset - Property filter's pathset propsRootObjType - VMWare object type (eg. VirtualMachine, HostSystem, ComputeResource,ResourcePool,Alarm) propsRootObj - VMWare object ID Responses\: success - The operation completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. no more - there are no more results to retrieve. Returns\: numberOfResults - Number of results from the query remaining to be retrieved returnResult - Query result item or operation result 09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.592c0736-0b77-48a6-93fc-e27059c5dc00.description=

09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.605ce812-dff8-471a-8251-1a7fdf586147.prompt=VMWare Host\: 09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.90e17d34-abd9-4350-afdd-3e00f5eb3946.prompt=datastore\: 09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.9b46be53-a4d0-459f-8e95-285f4854c779.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.b02d1c5e-ac17-4ec9-9136-4c6335ec8668.prompt=VMWare User\: 09fc1eae-9bc4-4048-a6ee-69492d1ca505.d84fab10-4fb7-481b-8bea-af928dab5d26.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
